The (n,alpha0), (n,alpha) and elastic cross-section magnitudes     825 1451
(MF=3, MT=2,107,800) were changed in December 2005 by Philip Page  825 1451
(LANL) from the ENDF/B-VI MOD 3 Evaluation (discussed above).      825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
The change made to the ENDF/B-VI MOD 3 version is that the         825 1451
cross-sections of all the 16O(n,alpha0) data in the region of      825 1451
laboratory neutron energy 2.4-8.9 MeV have been been reduced by    825 1451
32%. The threshold is at 2.4 MeV. The total 16O n cross-section    825 1451
is fixed, so that the difference is put into the elastic 16O n     825 1451
cross-section (in the region 2.4-8.9 MeV). The 16O(n,alpha)        825 1451
cross-section is also changed to reflect the new 16O(n,alpha0)     825 1451
cross-section.                                                     825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
The logic is as follows: The ENDF/B-VI evaluation of               825 1451
16O(n,alpha0) used three evaluations spliced together: one from    825 1451
0-3.4 MeV (KAPL), one from 3.4-6.25 MeV (R-matrix, Gerry Hale),    825 1451
and one from 6.25-30 MeV. Inspection of the ENDF/B-VI file and     825 1451
comments in the file indicate that continuity is preserved at      825 1451
the boundary of these three evaluations. Since the Bair and        825 1451
Haas data [Ba73] in the 3.2-6.8 MeV neutron energy region          825 1451
set the scale of the R-matrix evaluation, it follows from          825 1451
continuity that it sets the scale of all three evaluations.        825 1451
Assuming that the new data from Harissopulos et al. [Ha05]         825 1451
for 3.0-8.9 MeV (neutron energy), which is on average 32%          825 1451
lower than the ENDF/B-VI R-matrix evaluation, are definitive,      825 1451
this implies the required reduction of 32% in the 3.0-8.9 MeV      825 1451
region.                                                            825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
Finer details:                                                     825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
(1) The 32% reduction estimate includes the averaged reduction     825 1451
estimates given by Harissopulos et al. [Ha05], it assumes their    825 1451
actual measured cross-section as reported (not the effective one   825 1451
they use to display their data), and takes into account the        825 1451
renormalization of the Bair and Haas data [Ba73] that was required 825 1451
for the ENDF/B-VI R-matrix analysis.                               825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
(2) Part of my philosophy with this new file is that one takes     825 1451
the view that the new data (Harissopulos [Ha05]) is 100% correct   825 1451
and the old data (Bair and Haas [Ba73]) is 100% wrong, as far      825 1451
as normalization.                                                  825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
(3) Since the ENDF/B-VI evaluation a new measurement by Heil       825 1451
[He02] was reported (corresponding to a maximum E_n of             825 1451
3.09 MeV). The energy range of this measurement falls in the       825 1451
0-3.4 MeV of the KAPL evaluation. The absolute normalization of    825 1451
the KAPL evaluation is set by the R-matrix evaluation from         825 1451
3.4-6.25 MeV. Since the Heil data [He02] follows the Drotleff data 825 1451
[Dr93], and the Drotleff data were renormalized 17% upwards in     825 1451
the R-matrix analysis, it means that the ENDF/B-VI evaluation      825 1451
should be renormalized downwards by 17% in the region of the Heil  825 1451
data (near threshold). To maintain continuity and uniformity in    825 1451
appearance with higher energies, the ENDF/B-VI evaluation is       825 1451
renormalized downwards by 32% not only from 3.0-8.9 MeV            825 1451
(as mentioned above), but from 2.4-8.9 MeV.                        825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
(4) There is a renormalization only over a finite region 2.4-8.9   825 1451
MeV. In the region above 8.9 MeV the cross-section is still what   825 1451
it used to be before. To retain continuity, I introduced a region  825 1451
around 8.9 MeV where the function was interpolated.  So the        825 1451
cross-section is technically continuous. The problem with          825 1451
changing the cross-section from 8.9-30 MeV from the former         825 1451
values is that you apparently have no empirical basis for doing    825 1451
so, since no new data is available in there regions.               825 1451
