The ENDF/B-VI evaluation is a combination of a new MOD 3 eval.     825 1451
below 30 MeV and the previous MOD 2 evaluation from 20 to 150 MeV. 825 1451
Both these evaluations are described below. The only change to the 825 1451
data above 30 MeV is to add tritium-production data, based on      825 1451
experimental yield data and spectra calculated with the GNASH      825 1451
Hauser-Feshbach/preequilibrium code.                               825 1451
  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the        825 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating, radioactivity, 825 1451
and shielding applications over the incident neutron energy range  825 1451
from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion here is divided into the  825 1451
region above and below 30 MeV.                                     825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
------------------------------------------------------------------ 825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 30 MeV                                 825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
  The evaluation above 30 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent     825 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission         825 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, alpha          825 1451
particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced (A>5)    825 1451
in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections with       825 1451
non-zero data above En = 30 MeV are:                               825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                 825 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                    825 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                            825 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions            825 1451
       MT=102  Radiative Capture Cross Section (Estimate Only)     825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                       825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle          825 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,       825 1451
               Deuterons, and Alphas; and Angle-Integrated         825 1451
               Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual Nuclei That     825 1451
               Are Stable Against Particle Emission                825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that       825 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n +     825 1451
O16 and p + O16 reactions [Ch96a]. We use the GNASH code system    825 1451
[Yo92], which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical, preequi-       825 1451
librium and direct-reaction theories. Coupled-channel and          825 1451
spherical optical model calculations are used to obtain particle   825 1451
transmission coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations,    825 1451
as well as for the elastic neutron angular distributions.          825 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual     825 1451
nuclei are included for reactions that exceed a cross section of   825 1451
approximately 1 nb at any energy. The energy-angle-correlations    825 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics        825 1451
[Ka88].                                                            825 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of   825 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96b]. The recoil    825 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in   825 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. Note     825 1451
that all other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass   825 1451
system. This method of representation requires a modification of   825 1451
the original ENDF-6 format.                                        825 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the   825 1451
GNASH calculations using either Feshbach, Kerman, Koonin (FKK)     825 1451
theory [Ch93] or the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77, Ka85].        825 1451
Discrete level data from nuclear data sheets were matched to       825 1451
continuum level densities using the formulation of Ignatyuk        825 1451
[Ig75] and pairing and shell parameters from the Cook [Co67]       825 1451
analysis. Neutron and charged-particle transmission coefficients   825 1451
were obtained from the optical potentials, as discussed below.     825 1451
Gamma-ray transmission coefficients were calculated using the      825 1451
Kopecky-Uhl model [Ko90].                                          825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
