 SUMMARY OF DATA VALIDATION OF THIS FILE AGAINST INTEGRAL          825 1451
    BENCHMARKS                                                     825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
  KAPL (Weinman, Caro, Lubitz) performed a number of data          825 1451
validation benchmark calculations to test the performance of this  825 1451
file (June-August 2001). This O16 evaluation gives consistently    825 1451
good results for the 21 CSWEG solution critical calculations, the  825 1451
liquid-oxygen broomstick neutron-transmission experiment, and the  825 1451
neutron age in water experiment (see below for more details).      825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
A) 21 CSWEG solution critical calculations.  Weinman calculated a  825 1451
 set of 21 ORNL and Rocky Flats benchmark solution criticals used  825 1451
 for CSEWG analyses. These calculations were run with ENDF/B-VI    825 1451
 release 5 U235 (Leal,Larson,wright,Derrien) and hydrogen (332.0   825 1451
 mbarns 2200m/s). Four different oxygen 16 cross section           825 1451
 evaluations were considered.                                      825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
 1. KAPL-Caro                                                      825 1451
 2. This evaluation (which contains the KAPL data below 3.4 MeV)   825 1451
 3. ENDF/B-VI MOD 2                                                825 1451
 4. JENDL 3.2                                                      825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
 All four O16 cross section evaluations gave good reactivity       825 1451
 responses versus our fitting parameter above-thermal-leakage ATL. 825 1451
 The ATL parameter is a sensitive trending variable to high energy 825 1451
 scattering cross sections.  All four O16 evaluations produced     825 1451
 eigenvalues whose mean values were all close to unity and only    825 1451
 the older ENDF/B-VI.2 cross section evaluation gave a slight      825 1451
 reactivity trend (about .0020 Delta Keff over the range). The     825 1451
 average eigenvalues and slopes are listed below.                  825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
     Library         Av. Keff    Slope                             825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
     KAPL-Caro       0.9993      +.0001                            825 1451
     This file       0.9996      +.0004                            825 1451
     ENDF/B-VI.2     1.0003      +.0032                            825 1451
     JENDL 3.2       1.0004      -.0002                            825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
 Thus the reactivity trend, labeled "slope" in the table above, is 825 1451
 much smaller in the new file compared to the previous ENDF/B-VI.2 825 1451
 evaluation.                                                       825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
B) The liquid-oxygen broomstick experiment. The oxygen window at   825 1451
 2.3 MeV is the most important feature at which energy the         825 1451
 greatest transmission takes place. The new evaluation produces    825 1451
 close to exact agreement with the experiment in the energy range  825 1451
 of the oxygen window. The previous ENDF/B-VI value is slightly    825 1451
 below the experimental value. At energies higher than 5.5 MeV,    825 1451
 the new evaluation produces slightly better results than does the 825 1451
 previous ENDF/B-VI results.                                       825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
C) Neutron age in water. KAPL obtained 26.4 to be compared         825 1451
 against an experimental value of 26.6 +/- 0.6. The previous       825 1451
 ENDF/B-VI file gave a result of 26.3.                             825 1451
                                                                   825 1451
Additionally, A.C. (Skip) Kahler at Bettis lab undertook           825 1451
benchmark testing of this file (memo, May 16, 2001) against        825 1451
thermal benchmarks documented in the Int. Handbook of Evaluated    825 1451
Criticality Safety Benchmark Experiments, as well as the L5 and    825 1451
L6 ORNL benchmarks. From a thermal reactor benchmark perspective,  825 1451
there is little to distinguish the performance of the present      825 1451
file compared to the previous ENDF file and JENDL-3.2.             825 1451
